<span class="header1">COMMUNICATIONS BUSINESS</span>
<p>The communication business needs people who can perform on and off the air. In this occupational field, you must have specialized knowledge in an area such as politics, art, sports, or business. Here are three examples.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Broadcaster</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/BC/C506027.jpg" width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Broadcaster" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>A broadcaster is responsible for putting the news or other programming on the air. As a broadcaster, you would probably begin your career by working behind the scenes.  It is very tough to become an "on air" broadcaster.  People are usually promoted into these positions after they have proven they can do "off air" work.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You need a degree in journalism or communications to work as a copywriter, the first job of a broadcaster. The more experience you have around a studio, the better your chances to do "on air" work.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>A broadcaster may earn as little as $23,000 and as much as $1,000,000 a year.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Advertising Copywriter</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/BC/C1737_31.jpg" width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Advertising Copywriter" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>If you like the idea of writing TV commercials or creating ads for magazines, you might become a copywriter.  As a copywriter, you need to love to write and be good at it.  You also need to work well under pressure.  Studios are fast paced.  You must be able to work in a hectic atmosphere.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You need a Bachelor's Degree in journalism or communications to become a copywriter.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>A copywriter's salary depends on his/her experience.  It depends on whether he or she has had commercial success as well.  Finally, it depends on the employer.  A copywriter can earn as much as $100,000.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

<span class="header1">ENTERTAINMENT BUSINESS</span>
<p>The occupations in this field allow people to work "behind the scenes" in show business. To be successful in this field you must understand business and have good people skills.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Business Manager</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/BC/43321.jpg" width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Business Manager" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>A business manager negotiates contracts, invests money, and makes deals for an entertainer.  In this job, you would make sure that the entertainer's money was handled well.  You would also help the entertainer find new places to perform.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You need a Bachelor's Degree in business administration or accounting for this job.  Some entertainers prefer a master's degree. You also need to know what the public wants to see and be able to search out opportunities.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The salary for a business manager can range from $15,000 to $500,000+.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />
 
	<span class="header2">Performing Arts Administrator</span><br /><br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>When you go to a theater to see a play, you see the actors working. You do not see others working behind the stage to make sure that things go smoothly.  A performing arts administrator is responsible for the entire production.  As a performing arts administrator, you would oversee the staff and make sure they performed their duties.  You would handle the production's money.  You would also oversee the day-to-day running of an acting company or theater.  It takes a long time to become a performing arts administrator.  Most performing arts administrator begin their career in the theater as actors, directors, or producers.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Most performing arts administrators have a master's degree or a Ph.D.  Experience in the theater will be very important to getting a job.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The yearly salary for a performing arts administrator ranges from $15,000 to $40,000.  The salary depends on the theater or production company hiring.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Production Assistant</span><br /><br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>It takes many people to put a television program on the air. A production assistant is one of these people.  As a production assistant, you would do whatever needed to be done to ensure a smooth production. You might type and deliver schedules for the production, hold the cue cards, answer phones, or file important papers. This is where many people begin their careers behind the camera.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You need a Bachelor's Degree in communications or broadcasting for most jobs.  If you are interested in any job in broadcasting, get as much experience as possible.  Try to find a part-time job in a studio.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The yearly salary range is $12,000 to $25,000.</blockquote>

